{"id":"0911.0935","submitter":"Craig Booth","authors":"C. M. Booth (Leiden), Joop Schaye (Leiden)","title":"Dark matter haloes determine the masses of supermassive black holes","comments":"MNRAS accepted. 6 pages, 3 figures. v2: Minor changes in response to\n  referee comments","journal-ref":"Mon.Not.Roy.Astron.Soc. 405: L1,2010","doi":"10.1111/j.1745-3933.2010.00832.x","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The energy and momentum deposited by the radiation from accretion onto the\nsupermassive black holes (BHs) that reside at the centres of virtually all\ngalaxies can halt or even reverse gas inflow, providing a natural mechanism for\nsupermassive BHs to regulate their growth and to couple their properties to\nthose of their host galaxies. However, it remains unclear whether this\nself-regulation occurs on the scale at which the BH is gravitationally\ndominant, on that of the stellar bulge, the galaxy, or that of the entire dark\nmatter halo. To answer this question, we use self-consistent simulations of the\nco-evolution of the BH and galaxy populations that reproduce the observed\ncorrelations between the masses of the BHs and the properties of their host\ngalaxies. We first confirm unambiguously that the BHs regulate their growth:\nthe amount of energy that the BHs inject into their surroundings remains\nunchanged when the fraction of the accreted rest mass energy that is injected,\nis varied by four orders of magnitude. The BHs simply adjust their masses so as\nto inject the same amount of energy. We then use simulations with artificially\nreduced star formation rates to demonstrate explicitly that BH mass is not set\nby the stellar mass. Instead, we find that it is determined by the mass of the\ndark matter halo with a secondary dependence on the halo concentration, of the\nform that would be expected if the halo binding energy were the fundamental\nproperty that controls the mass of the BH. We predict that the logarithmic\nslope of the relation between dark matter halo mass and black hole mass is\n1.55+/-0.05 and that the scatter around the mean relation in part reflects the\nscatter in the halo concentration-mass relation.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 5 Nov 2009 16:25:53 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 16 Feb 2010 10:18:22 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-05-14"}
{"id":"0911.0945","submitter":"Ryan Requist","authors":"Ryan Requist, Oleg Pankratov","title":"Adiabatic approximation in time-dependent reduced-density-matrix\n  functional theory","comments":"18 pages, 8 figures; thoroughly revised","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A, vol. 81, 042519 (2010)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.81.042519","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  With the aim of describing real-time electron dynamics, we introduce an\nadiabatic approximation for the equation of motion of the one-body\nreduced-density matrix (one-matrix). The eigenvalues of the one-matrix, which\nrepresent the occupation numbers of single-particle orbitals, are obtained from\nthe constrained minimization of the instantaneous ground state energy\nfunctional rather than from their dynamical equations. To clarify the\nmotivation for this minimization condition, we discuss a sequence of adiabatic\nenergy functionals, each obeying a minimum principle. The performance of the\napproximation vis-a`-vis nonadiabatic effects is assessed in real-time\nsimulations for a two-site Hubbard model. Due to the presence of\nLandau-Zener-type transitions, the system evolves into a nonstationary state\nwith persistent oscillations in the observables. The amplitude and phase of the\noscillations exhibit resonance behavior both with respect to the strength of\nthe electron-electron interaction and the rate of variation of the external\npotential. Both types of resonances have the same origin -- the interference of\ndynamical and scattering phases.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 5 Nov 2009 18:07:49 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 17 Mar 2010 19:37:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-09-18"}
